    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://medium.com/codex/after-six-months-of-using-the-m1-pro-the-verdict-is-in-d112909c5731"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">After Six Months Of Using The M1 Pro, The Verdict Is In</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">A 180-day review of the 16‚Äù MacBook M1 Pro and M1 Max</h3><p>medium.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://medium.com/can-you-really-develop-apps-on-the-m1-ipad-air-66f1ef0677f3"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">Can You Really Develop Apps On The M1 iPad Air?</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">The verdict is in. I tried building an iOS and a web app‚Ä¶</h3><p>levelup.gitconnected.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So, to make this an easy read for you and make myself not feel like I am regurgitating my 2020 and 2021 reviews, <strong>I decided in true software engineering fashion to do a diff review!</strong> üòÅ I will only mention what‚Äôs different, worse, or better about the M2 Air. For everything else, I‚Äôll just refer to my M1 and M1 Pro/Max articles, which are already pretty in-depth. If you‚Äôre curious about a non software engineering perspective, you‚Äôre welcome to <a href="https://attilavago.medium.com/a-laymans-review-of-the-m2-macbook-air-for-everyday-users-cf8ffc99c8c1" target="_self">read that in my layman‚Äôs review</a>. I would rather not bore all readers with details they aren‚Äôt concerned with, so broke the review up into two. Genius! Absolute genius! Now with that self-patting on the back out of the way, <strong>let‚Äôs decide if the M2 Air will be your next developer daily driver or not.</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://attilavago.medium.com/a-laymans-review-of-the-m2-macbook-air-for-everyday-users-cf8ffc99c8c1"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">A Layman‚Äôs Review Of The M2 MacBook Air For Everyday Users</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">Let‚Äôs not bore anyone with the tech stuff, but focus on the day-to-day. Does the M2 Air deliver?</h3><p>attilavago.medium.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">It‚Äôs all about that aluminium, baby‚Ä¶</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Many of us software engineers are so used to 15‚Äù and 16‚Äù machines that it‚Äôs almost shocking when we manage to do our work on a smaller and lighter machine, and here I want to focus first on the lightness aspect.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I am aware that working in the office is not as trendy as it used to be, but there are still plenty of engineers who do that, even if just once or twice a week. With companies doing their 3-year hardware refresh cycles, I have seen many coders end up with the new 16‚Äù M1 Pro/Max. The massive downside of that machine is that lugging it to the office and back feels very 90s. In contrast, <strong>picking the M2 Air up and walking anywhere, any distance feels a lot more 2022</strong>, as you genuinely don‚Äôt feel you‚Äôre carrying something.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The other benefit of lightness with the M2 is the fact that <strong>now you can pop over to a colleague‚Äôs desk, or even just walk around the office with the laptop open, holding it in one hand</strong> while explaining some code you wrote, doing a commit, whatever it is, you can do it one-handed. I genuinely think software companies should start looking at the M2 Air as a viable machine for many of their software engineers, instead of blanket-buying or leasing the top spec 14‚Äù or 16‚Äù MacBook Pros.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">By far the biggest selling-point of the M2 Air is its size and weight. Portability matters to developers too.</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">There is of course <strong>a downside to smaller size, and that‚Äôs the screen real-estate</strong>. No matter how you want to flip reality here, this is a less than 14‚Äù screen, and when it comes to coding, I found that be that WebStorm, VsCode, Xcode or Android Studio, after a couple of hours, the screen size becomes a limitation that only the 16‚Äù model can solve, albeit only partially. <strong>If your only screen is going to be the laptop‚Äôs screen, I would not recommend getting the M2 Air.</strong> It‚Äôs a beautiful screen, no doubt, but simply not wide and tall enough for extended coding sessions. Sure it‚Äôs fine for the odd day you‚Äôre on the move, or in a meeting room sneaking in some code while designers fight about font-sizes and shades of grey, but otherwise you‚Äôll be doing yourself a disservice going for a device with such a small screen. <strong>Of course, none of these limitations exist if you‚Äôre going to connect to an extended monitor, even if it‚Äôs just another 13‚Äù screen</strong> or even an iPad.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">The specs you want !== the specs you need</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I think it has now been established that an <strong>8 GB RAM model will not be suitable for most software developers</strong>. This is not unexpected, and while you might really want that to be true, and frankly so did I back in 2020, the reality of it is, that other than occasional and fairly light coding projects, the M2 on 8 GB of memory will simply feel like a bottleneck. Having said that, <strong>the 256 GB SSD ‚Äî yes, even with its lower speed ‚Äî is passable if you‚Äôre really just about coding and building apps</strong> without using any virtual machines or dockers.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>With 16 GB of memory, however, things change drastically for the better.</strong> Because I am terrible at closing anything, I was simultaneously running WebStorm, Android Studio and an iOS emulator with up to 50 tabs open in Chrome and Safari, and didn‚Äôt experience any issues. Of course adding dockers to that already ridiculous situation changed things again, but really, 16 GB of RAM should allow you to work with one or two moderately sized dockers.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4"><mark>Most software engineers should go for 16 GB RAM and 512 GB SSD. All other configurations are a small niche.</mark></p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now, what about 24 GB RAM? I said this before, and I‚Äôll say it again, simply don‚Äôt. <strong>Unless portability is the most important aspect for you, you‚Äôre better off with the 14‚Äù M1 Pro</strong>, though in fairness you‚Äôll have to go up a spec to 32 GB of memory, which does cost nearly an extra 500 bucks. Ugh. There is no way around it, though. If you‚Äôre a software developer heavily reliant on virtual machines, the thing you don‚Äôt want less of, is RAM!</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://medium.com/codex/dont-fully-spec-your-m2-macbook-air-out-c8c0afd6085e"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">Don‚Äôt Fully Spec Your M2 MacBook Air Out</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">It will be the worst deal ever, and you have better options‚Ä¶</h3><p>medium.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What about the extra 2 GPU cores? <strong>I went with the 8-core model because I can‚Äôt really see what software engineer would make very good use of two extra GPU cores.</strong> Perhaps someone building games, but I would also argue that game developers probably should opt for a MacBook Pro instead of the M2 Air.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Every day I‚Äôm shuffling‚Ä¶</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">It has now been exactly 2 weeks of using the M2 Air exclusively. I did not even turn on the M1 Pro during this time. Let me put it this way, <strong>I am not missing the Pro. At all.</strong> With an extended screen ‚Äî Studio Display ‚Äî this has been a very smooth experience so far.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I have built Flutter apps, ran iOS and Android emulators, ran web projects in React, ran Xcode projects, a Next.js project, vanilla web projects, used nGrok, did accessibility reviews with Wave and AXE, <strong>I have done everything I would normally do on my 16" Pro machine.</strong> By the way, if you‚Äôre into Flutter development, you‚Äôll want to check this quick note on CocoaPods installation on the M1 and M2.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://medium.com/bricksnbrackets/how-to-correctly-install-cocoapods-on-m1-m2-6abe3736c221"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">How To Correctly Install CocoaPods On Apple Silicon M1 & M2?</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">The painless method, before you start pulling your hair‚Ä¶</h3><p>medium.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Additionally, <strong>for this laptop specifically, I also played around building a Zoom app</strong>. I consider this a somewhat more exotic development workflow as it requires <strong>running ngrok with an open Zoom meeting instance</strong>, which lends you with up to two additional web views. Zoom itself is a pretty resource-hungry application, so wanted to make sure I was still able to have a good development experience. I am pleased to report that, yes, I did not experience any issues. Having said that, <strong>I did have to close Android Studio and Pixelmator Pro ‚Äî both apps I wasn‚Äôt using ‚Äî at that point, as Ulysses started lagging. </strong>While I would not call Ulysses an exemplary app in terms of optimisation, seeing choppiness while writing does indicate the machine is struggling somewhere. Looking at the memory utilisation and pressure, that wasn‚Äôt it though, so likely my CPU cores started juggling just a bit too much at the same time.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To further add to my array of exotic development tests, <strong>I also ran my Wasp project, which I was happy to see was running super-smoothly</strong>, no issues whatsoever. I recommend checking <a style="color:green" href="https://medium.com/u/5c776237f273?source=post_page-----d6f609cc124f--------------------------------" target="_self">Wasp Lang</a> out, it‚Äôs in Alpha at the time of writing, but the more I think about it, the more impressed I am by what I was able to achieve with it in just 30 or so minutes!</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://medium.com/bricksnbrackets/i-tried-wasp-a-dsl-for-modern-web-applications-c125d334eb2a"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">I Tried Wasp, A DSL For Modern Web Applications</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">I got special access to the Alpha release of the language, so I did what every curious programmer would do‚Ä¶</h3><p>medium.com</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">I threw anything I could think of at the M2 Air, and it kept truckin‚Äô. Not even a beach-ball, come to think of it!</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In terms of <strong>battery-life</strong>, doing all these development workflows resulted in a fairly expected experience, but I would even say <strong>slightly better than on the M1</strong>. Doing a bit of maths, <strong>the only somewhat worrying dev flow in terms of battery-life is the Zoom app one</strong>, and that‚Äôs because Zoom is constantly open in a meeting, which means your webcam and mics are also on. That seems to result in around <strong>7 hours of continuous development</strong>. With perhaps 5‚Äì10% battery left. <strong>For every other kind of dev workflow, you can expect 8‚Äì10, potentially even 12 hours</strong> of development time on a single charge. That easily covers a full working day.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>Heat-management is also a non-issue.</strong> The M2 Air deals with software development beautifully, and I have yet to see the temperatures go above 80 Celsius when coding and compiling, and even when it does, it‚Äôs an extremely short burst of just a few seconds. Long story short, <strong>for temps to go really high, above 90 or 100 Celsius, you need a build that runs longer than a minute</strong>, and with M2 being pretty fast, many projects won‚Äôt ever trigger those temperatures. <strong>My </strong><code>.ipa</code><strong> build took 47s, during which I saw one of the efficiency cores jump to 85 Celsius</strong>, all other cores being at anywhere between 40-70 Celsius.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">It can‚Äôt ‚Äúall be good under the hood‚Äù, can it?</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I would like to be cynical, but my findings don‚Äôt really allow me to. If you want me to be nitpicky though, I can certainly try if that helps you make a more informed decision, so <strong>here are a couple of tiny annoyances</strong>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">When you pick the machine up by its front edge, you‚Äôll inadvertently find yourself opening the lid, which then wakes the machine up or turns it on, so you‚Äôll have to create new habits around avoiding that.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The sound is really not that great, and I know that developers aren‚Äôt all too fussed about it, but I do think it‚Äôs worth knowing that if you like immersive music while coding, you‚Äôre not going to get that from the M2 MacBook Air (nor the M1 MacBook Air in fairness). <strong>All I am saying, don‚Äôt sell your headphones.</strong> Those who decide to downgrade from an M1 Pro/Max, you‚Äôll be underwhelmed, and you will want a decent pair of headphones if you don‚Äôt already have them.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">With the M2 Air, you really need to look for the negatives, and that in itself says a lot.</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">MagSafe, while not a negative in and of itself, I also don‚Äôt really see it as a positive when it comes to software developers. Given that our workloads will rarely require us to work while plugged in, and when connected to a monitor with power delivery, this laptop will charge just fine. You can‚Äôt connect more than one external screen anyway, so <strong>the value of MagSafe, as cool as it is, kind of diminishes to near irrelevance</strong>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Git commit -m ‚Äúthe verdict‚Äù</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I had a suspicion this would end up being the case, and spending two weeks with a mid-tier M2 Air that I am now going to keep and make my daily driver for the foreseeable future as well, confirms that.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>With utmost sincerity, the M2 Air is a very capable machine at 16 GB RAM and 512 GB SSD configuration.</strong> At this spec, 50‚Äì70% of software developers will have no reason not to get it. And this is good news. Even at mid-spec the M2 Air is cheaper than the 14‚Äù Pro, and while the latter does bring some extras to the table, none of those are in the <em>‚Äúneed‚Äù</em> category for most software developers. <strong>In many ways, the M2 Air is the best of both worlds.</strong> You‚Äôre getting a hip new machine, with the latest Apple Silicon, while paying less money and getting more portability.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I think that a fairly large proportion of current software developers use overpowered machines, specs that will never get utilised, an unnecessary overkill, waste of money and resources. The M2 Air solves that problem.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">The M2 Air is good enough to steal considerable market-share away from the M1 Pro.</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
